<methodology slug="devops-platform-crossplane">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>devops-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Use Crossplane to build Kubernetes-native infrastructure compositions: developers submit simple CRD claims, Crossplane reconciles multi-resource AWS/GCP/Azure stacks with security defaults built in.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>crossplane</tag>
      <tag>kubernetes</tag>
      <tag>infrastructure-as-code</tag>
      <tag>platform-engineering</tag>
      <tag>cncf</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>platform</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="devops-platform-idp-core"/>
      <ref slug="devops-platform-golden-paths"/>
      <ref slug="devops-platform-policy-finops"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Crossplane: Kubernetes-Native Infrastructure Compositions</title>

    <summary>Crossplane extends Kubernetes with Composite Resource Definitions (XRDs) so platform teams define infrastructure abstractions (Database, Cache, Network) as custom CRDs. Developers submit simple claim objects; Crossplane reconciles the full multi-resource stack with security defaults embedded. This gives developers a self-service API surface while platform teams retain control over security, cost, and compliance through the composition layer.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Traditional IaC (Terraform, CloudFormation) requires developers to understand provider-specific resources and security configurations. Crossplane inverts this: the platform team encodes best practices into a Composition once, and developers interact only with a simple claim API (Database, Cache, Cluster). The Kubernetes reconciliation loop ensures desired state is continuously enforced — drift correction is automatic, not manual.</p>
      <p>As a CNCF project, Crossplane integrates natively with GitOps tools (ArgoCD, Flux), enabling infrastructure and application deployments to share the same GitOps pipeline. Claims are versioned in Git like application code.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Platform team building self-service infrastructure abstractions on top of AWS, GCP, or Azure.</item>
        <item>Orgs already using Kubernetes who want infrastructure provisioning to follow the same GitOps workflow as application deployments.</item>
        <item>Multi-cloud environments where the same developer-facing API (e.g., Database claim) must provision to different cloud backends depending on environment.</item>
        <item>Infrastructure that needs continuous reconciliation (drift correction) rather than one-time apply.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Teams not running Kubernetes — Crossplane requires a Kubernetes cluster as its control plane; the overhead is not justified without an existing cluster.</item>
        <item>Simple single-resource provisioning where a Terraform module achieves the same result with less operational complexity.</item>
        <item>Orgs without Kubernetes expertise — Crossplane debugging requires understanding Kubernetes reconciliation loops and CRD status conditions.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="xrd-and-composition">
      <p>Every Crossplane infrastructure abstraction consists of two Kubernetes objects: a CompositeResourceDefinition (XRD) that defines the API schema, and a Composition that maps claim fields to provider-specific resources. Together they are the infrastructure equivalent of a golden path template.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every Crossplane XRD MUST define both a composite type (XDatabase) and a claim type (Database). The claim is what developers interact with in their namespace. Compositions MUST embed security defaults that cannot be overridden by claim parameters — storageEncrypted: true, publiclyAccessible: false, and deleteProtection: false in non-production are non-negotiable platform defaults. Developers MUST NOT be able to set storageEncrypted: false through the claim API.</statement>
        <rationale>Security defaults embedded in the Composition layer are enforced at the platform level, not through policy review. This achieves near-100% security compliance (Netflix Wall-E model) by making insecure configurations impossible to request, not forbidden by policy.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="XRD definition — Database composite type with claim">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
apiVersion: apiextensions.crossplane.io/v1
kind: CompositeResourceDefinition
metadata:
  name: xdatabases.platform.example.com
spec:
  group: platform.example.com
  names:
    kind: XDatabase
    plural: xdatabases
  claimNames:
    kind: Database
    plural: databases
  versions:
    - name: v1alpha1
      served: true
      referenceable: true
      schema:
        openAPIV3Schema:
          type: object
          properties:
            spec:
              type: object
              properties:
                size:
                  type: string
                  enum: [small, medium, large]
                  default: small
                environment:
                  type: string
                  enum: [development, staging, production]
              required:
                - environment
]]></code>
        <note>The schema exposes only size and environment to developers. All other RDS properties (encryption, multiAZ, backup) are controlled in the Composition, invisible to the developer.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Developer claim — what the developer actually writes">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# my-database.yaml — what the developer writes and commits to Git
apiVersion: platform.example.com/v1alpha1
kind: Database
metadata:
  name: user-db
spec:
  size: small
  environment: production
]]></code>
        <note>The developer writes 8 lines. Crossplane reconciles this into an RDS instance, security group, subnet group, parameter group, and Kubernetes Secret — all with security defaults enforced.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Exposing all RDS parameters directly to developers">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# Anti-pattern: direct provider resource claim
apiVersion: rds.aws.crossplane.io/v1alpha1
kind: DBInstance
metadata:
  name: user-db
spec:
  forProvider:
    storageEncrypted: false    # developer disabled encryption
    publiclyAccessible: true   # developer opened to internet
    instanceClass: db.r5.8xlarge  # no cost control
]]></code>
        <note>Direct provider resources expose every parameter, making security defaults bypassable and cost controls impossible.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="composition-patches">
      <p>Crossplane Compositions use patch sets to map claim field values to provider resource properties. The size-to-instanceClass mapping is the canonical example — it translates the developer's abstract "small/medium/large" into specific cloud resource configurations while enforcing environment-appropriate defaults.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Full AWS RDS Composition with patch sets">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
apiVersion: apiextensions.crossplane.io/v1
kind: Composition
metadata:
  name: database-postgresql-aws
  labels:
    provider: aws
    engine: postgresql
spec:
  compositeTypeRef:
    apiVersion: platform.example.com/v1alpha1
    kind: XDatabase

  patchSets:
    - name: common-tags
      patches:
        - type: FromCompositeFieldPath
          fromFieldPath: metadata.labels[team]
          toFieldPath: spec.forProvider.tags[0].value

  resources:
    - name: rds-instance
      base:
        apiVersion: rds.aws.crossplane.io/v1alpha1
        kind: DBInstance
        spec:
          forProvider:
            region: eu-central-1
            engine: postgres
            engineVersion: "15"
            storageType: gp3
            storageEncrypted: true          # non-overridable default
            publiclyAccessible: false       # non-overridable default
            autoMinorVersionUpgrade: true
            backupRetentionPeriod: 7
            deletionProtection: false
      patches:
        - type: FromCompositeFieldPath
          fromFieldPath: spec.size
          toFieldPath: spec.forProvider.instanceClass
          transforms:
            - type: map
              map:
                small: db.t3.micro
                medium: db.t3.medium
                large: db.r5.large
        - type: FromCompositeFieldPath
          fromFieldPath: spec.size
          toFieldPath: spec.forProvider.allocatedStorage
          transforms:
            - type: map
              map:
                small: 20
                medium: 100
                large: 500
        - type: FromCompositeFieldPath
          fromFieldPath: spec.environment
          toFieldPath: spec.forProvider.multiAZ
          transforms:
            - type: map
              map:
                development: false
                staging: false
                production: true

    - name: db-secret
      base:
        apiVersion: kubernetes.crossplane.io/v1alpha1
        kind: Object
        spec:
          forProvider:
            manifest:
              apiVersion: v1
              kind: Secret
              metadata:
                namespace: default
              type: Opaque
]]></code>
        <note>multiAZ is automatically true for production, false for dev/staging. The developer never sees this setting — the platform makes the right infrastructure decision based on environment context.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="terraform-module-pattern">
      <p>When Crossplane is not available (non-Kubernetes environments), Terraform modules serve as the equivalent composition layer. A platform-standard EKS module encodes the same security defaults that a Crossplane XRD would provide.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Platform Terraform modules MUST set cluster_endpoint_public_access = false and cluster_endpoint_private_access = true by default for all Kubernetes cluster modules. Public endpoint access MUST NOT be the default. Modules MUST output cluster_endpoint and cluster_certificate_authority_data for downstream consumption without requiring module consumers to access the provider state directly.</statement>
        <rationale>Public Kubernetes API endpoints are the most common misconfiguration leading to cluster compromise. Embedding the private-only default in the module means all EKS clusters provisioned through the platform golden path are secure by construction, not by policy reminder.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Platform-standard EKS Terraform module">
        <code lang="hcl"><![CDATA[
# modules/eks-cluster/main.tf
module "eks" {
  source  = "terraform-aws-modules/eks/aws"
  version = "~> 20.0"

  cluster_name    = var.cluster_name
  cluster_version = "1.29"

  vpc_id     = var.vpc_id
  subnet_ids = var.private_subnet_ids

  cluster_endpoint_public_access  = false  # platform default: private only
  cluster_endpoint_private_access = true

  enable_cluster_creator_admin_permissions = true

  cluster_addons = {
    coredns = {
      most_recent = true
    }
    kube-proxy = {
      most_recent = true
    }
    vpc-cni = {
      most_recent = true
    }
    aws-ebs-csi-driver = {
      most_recent = true
    }
  }

  eks_managed_node_groups = {
    general = {
      instance_types = ["t3.medium"]
      min_size       = 2
      max_size       = 10
      desired_size   = 3

      labels = {
        role = "general"
      }

      tags = {
        Environment = var.environment
        Team        = "platform"
      }
    }
  }

  tags = var.tags
}

# Output for platform consumption
output "cluster_endpoint" {
  value = module.eks.cluster_endpoint
}

output "cluster_certificate_authority_data" {
  value = module.eks.cluster_certificate_authority_data
}
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="crossplane-llm-prompts">
      <p>LLM prompts for Crossplane composition design and Terraform module generation.</p>

      <prompt purpose="Design a Crossplane composition for an infrastructure resource">
        <![CDATA[
Design a Crossplane composition for [resource type].

Resource: [database/cache/storage/network]
Cloud provider: [AWS/GCP/Azure]
Variants needed: [development/staging/production]

Composition should:
1. Define CompositeResourceDefinition (XRD) with claim
2. Provide sensible defaults
3. Allow customization where needed
4. Include security best practices (non-overridable)
5. Set up monitoring/alerting
6. Handle credentials securely (output as Kubernetes Secret)

Output:
- XRD YAML
- Composition YAML
- Example claim YAML
- Documentation for developers
]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="Generate a Terraform module for a platform component">
        <![CDATA[
Generate a Terraform module for [platform component].

Component: [EKS cluster/RDS database/VPC/S3 bucket]
Requirements: [list specific requirements]
Security: [encryption, network isolation, IAM]

Module should:
1. Follow Terraform best practices
2. Use variables for customization
3. Include sensible defaults
4. Output necessary values for consumers
5. Include examples in README

Output: Complete module with main.tf, variables.tf, outputs.tf, README.md
]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Exposing raw provider CRDs (e.g., rds.aws.crossplane.io/v1alpha1 DBInstance) directly to developers instead of building XRD compositions.</description>
      <reason>Raw provider resources expose hundreds of configuration options. Developers will misconfigure security settings, pick oversized instances, and bypass cost controls. The composition layer is what makes Crossplane a platform tool rather than just another IaC format.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Using Crossplane as a one-shot provisioning tool without leveraging continuous reconciliation.</description>
      <reason>Crossplane's primary value over Terraform is the Kubernetes reconciliation loop — it continuously corrects drift. Treating it as one-shot apply loses the drift correction benefit and leaves you with Terraform's operational model at Crossplane's operational complexity.</reason>
    </antipattern>

